n><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NASS is a national membership organisation for Independent and Non-Maintained Special Schools.  We have over 220 members – almost 50% of these are registered as children’s homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As you may recall, Claire Dorer, Chief Executive of NASS, gave evidence to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Education Committee as part of their inquiry. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, since </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">then </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Government has published its response to the consultation on residential care reform and NASS would like to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> highlight a couple of concerns we have with the proposed reforms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ahead of your session with Children’s Minister Edward Timpson MP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NASS would like to put on record that we would have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">preferred the Government to have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">waited until the Education Committee’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inquiry was concluded before publishing their response. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">New homes in safe areas</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government have confirmed plans to change</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> regulations so </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">new homes </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">only open in </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">safe</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> areas, run by competent providers and ensuring homes already open in less safe areas evidence that they can keep children safe, or face closure</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would like to put on record that r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">egulations can be valuable in setting “absolutes” which must be followed.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> However, they are crude instruments in effecting long-lasting cultural change. Change in the residential child care system will not occur through regulation alone and specifically not regulation which largely focuses on the responsibilities of homes thems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">elves</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would like to stress that r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">esidential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hild </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are is a complex system where factors beyond what goes on in the homes have a significant impact on the sector. For example, because of the high cost of property, new homes will be more likely to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">locate in relatively cheaper areas and some areas, especially in London, will struggle to attract new providers. Risk assessing an area offers something in some circumstances but covers one dimension in a wider issue.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Currently no children's home can feel </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">safe secure and cared for because of the many pressures, especially those concerni</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng finance and regulation, that</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are being applied to them.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would question the practicalities of this proposal and specifically how Local Authorities will determine that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">placements are in “safe”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">areas? </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would also like to raise the issue that if a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> previously safe area is identified as now being potentially unsafe, what is reasonable action to take? A very small home might feasibly consider relocation. However, a 120 plac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e school, additionally registered as a children’s home, with a 100 year plus history, land, buildings and upwards of 300 staff could not move. Whilst it could be potentially useful to better understand your area, it is not likely that it is within an indiv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">idual home’s ability to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">able to mitigate against all identified risks. It is unclear whether this would be considered an acceptable position or if the home would be considered as negligent.</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Questions to ask Edward Timpson MP</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">How will the Minister</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ensu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that this proposal works practically on the ground and does not result in a shortfall of places in children’s homes?</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Out of area placements</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Under proposals by the Government</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0b0c0c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> only senior council officials in charge of children’s services will be able to place children out of area and only when they judge it to be the right decision for a child to be moved away from their home area.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Though th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oposal has good intentions, we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fear that it will add another layer of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bureaucracy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> could mitigate against young people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> receiving their entitlements.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local Authorities need to have robust regimes for the identification, assessment, planning, delivery, monitoring and evaluation and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to be able to justif</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y them in Ofsted Inspections.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This measure will do nothing to attend to the deve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lopment of strategic commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that should deliver the right placement at the right time for the right child.  We are already encountering unintended con</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sequences from thinking that prioritises local placement. We need local, regional and national to be firmly delivering safety, choice and specialism. Out of area placements may be well justified. The pressure on Local Authorities to place within their own </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">boundaries can act counter to meeting the needs of a young person. </span><br /></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Questions to ask Edward Timpson MP</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">How can the Minister be sure that this proposal will not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lead to some children and young people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">facing addition barriers to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> receiving the s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">upport they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are entitled to?</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">bout us</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 1.4pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The National Association of Independent Schools and Non-Maintained Special Schools (NASS) is a membership organisation catering for approximately 6,000 very vulnerable children and young people in over 210 schools and organisati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ons. It provides information, support and training to its members to advance the education of children and young people with SEN. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 1.4pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 1.4pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-top-color:#c0c0c0; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:0pt; padding-top:1pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> | </span><span style="color:#808080; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:3pt">Page</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>